2811// Helper function for GenerateTargetSpecificAttrChecks that alters the 'Test'
2812// parameter with only a single check type, if applicable.
2813static void GenerateTargetSpecificAttrCheck(const Record *R, std::string &Test,
2814 std::string *FnName,
2815 StringRef ListName,
2816 StringRef CheckAgainst,
2817 StringRef Scope) {
2818 if (!R->isValueUnset(ListName)) {
2819 Test += " && (";
2820 std::vector<StringRef> Items = R->getValueAsListOfStrings(ListName);
2821 for (auto I = Items.begin(), E = Items.end(); I != E; ++I) {
2822 StringRef Part = *I;
2823 Test += CheckAgainst;
2824 Test += " == ";
2825 Test += Scope;
2826 Test += Part;
2827 if (I + 1 != E)
2828 Test += " || ";
2829 if (FnName)
2830 *FnName += Part;
2831 }
2832 Test += ")";
2833 }
2834}
2835
2836// Generate a conditional expression to check if the current target satisfies
2837// the conditions for a TargetSpecificAttr record, and append the code for
2838// those checks to the Test string. If the FnName string pointer is non-null,
2839// append a unique suffix to distinguish this set of target checks from other
2840// TargetSpecificAttr records.
2841static void GenerateTargetSpecificAttrChecks(const Record *R,
2842 std::vector<StringRef> &Arches,
2843 std::string &Test,
2844 std::string *FnName) {
2845 // It is assumed that there will be an llvm::Triple object
2846 // named "T" and a TargetInfo object named "Target" within
2847 // scope that can be used to determine whether the attribute exists in
2848 // a given target.
2849 Test += "true";
2850 // If one or more architectures is specified, check those. Arches are handled
2851 // differently because GenerateTargetRequirements needs to combine the list
2852 // with ParseKind.
2853 if (!Arches.empty()) {
2854 Test += " && (";
2855 for (auto I = Arches.begin(), E = Arches.end(); I != E; ++I) {
2856 StringRef Part = *I;
2857 Test += "T.getArch() == llvm::Triple::";
2858 Test += Part;
2859 if (I + 1 != E)
2860 Test += " || ";
2861 if (FnName)
2862 *FnName += Part;
2863 }
2864 Test += ")";
2865 }
2866
2867 // If the attribute is specific to particular OSes, check those.
2868 GenerateTargetSpecificAttrCheck(R, Test, FnName, "OSes", "T.getOS()",
2869 "llvm::Triple::");
2870
2871 // If one or more CXX ABIs are specified, check those as well.
2872 GenerateTargetSpecificAttrCheck(R, Test, FnName, "CXXABIs",
2873 "Target.getCXXABI().getKind()",
2874 "TargetCXXABI::");
2875 // If one or more object formats is specified, check those.
2876 GenerateTargetSpecificAttrCheck(R, Test, FnName, "ObjectFormats",
2877 "T.getObjectFormat()", "llvm::Triple::");
2878}
2879
2880static void GenerateHasAttrSpellingStringSwitch(
2881 const std::vector<Record *> &Attrs, raw_ostream &OS,
2882 const std::string &Variety = "", const std::string &Scope = "") {
2883 for (const auto *Attr : Attrs) {
2884 // C++11-style attributes have specific version information associated with
2885 // them. If the attribute has no scope, the version information must not
2886 // have the default value (1), as that's incorrect. Instead, the unscoped
2887 // attribute version information should be taken from the SD-6 standing
2888 // document, which can be found at:
2889 // https://isocpp.org/std/standing-documents/sd-6-sg10-feature-test-recommendations
2890 int Version = 1;
2891
2892 if (Variety == "CXX11") {
2893 std::vector<Record *> Spellings = Attr->getValueAsListOfDefs("Spellings");
2894 for (const auto &Spelling : Spellings) {
2895 if (Spelling->getValueAsString("Variety") == "CXX11") {
2896 Version = static_cast<int>(Spelling->getValueAsInt("Version"));
2897 if (Scope.empty() && Version == 1)
2898 PrintError(Spelling->getLoc(), "C++ standard attributes must "
2899 "have valid version information.");
2900 break;
2901 }
2902 }
2903 }
2904
2905 std::string Test;
2906 if (Attr->isSubClassOf("TargetSpecificAttr")) {
2907 const Record *R = Attr->getValueAsDef("Target");
2908 std::vector<StringRef> Arches = R->getValueAsListOfStrings("Arches");
2909 GenerateTargetSpecificAttrChecks(R, Arches, Test, nullptr);
2910
2911 // If this is the C++11 variety, also add in the LangOpts test.
2912 if (Variety == "CXX11")
2913 Test += " && LangOpts.CPlusPlus11";
2914 else if (Variety == "C2x")
2915 Test += " && LangOpts.DoubleSquareBracketAttributes";
2916 } else if (Variety == "CXX11")
2917 // C++11 mode should be checked against LangOpts, which is presumed to be
2918 // present in the caller.
2919 Test = "LangOpts.CPlusPlus11";
2920 else if (Variety == "C2x")
2921 Test = "LangOpts.DoubleSquareBracketAttributes";
2922
2923 std::string TestStr =
2924 !Test.empty() ? Test + " ? " + llvm::itostr(Version) + " : 0" : "1";
2925 std::vector<FlattenedSpelling> Spellings = GetFlattenedSpellings(*Attr);
2926 for (const auto &S : Spellings)
2927 if (Variety.empty() || (Variety == S.variety() &&
2928 (Scope.empty() || Scope == S.nameSpace())))
2929 OS << " .Case(\"" << S.name() << "\", " << TestStr << ")\n";
2930 }
2931 OS << " .Default(0);\n";
2932}

2934// Emits the list of spellings for attributes.
2935void EmitClangAttrHasAttrImpl(RecordKeeper &Records, raw_ostream &OS) {
2936 emitSourceFileHeader("Code to implement the __has_attribute logic", OS);
2937
2938 // Separate all of the attributes out into four group: generic, C++11, GNU,
2939 // and declspecs. Then generate a big switch statement for each of them.
2940 std::vector<Record *> Attrs = Records.getAllDerivedDefinitions("Attr");
2941 std::vector<Record *> Declspec, Microsoft, GNU, Pragma;
2942 std::map<std::string, std::vector<Record *>> CXX, C2x;
2943
2944 // Walk over the list of all attributes, and split them out based on the
2945 // spelling variety.
2946 for (auto *R : Attrs) {
2947 std::vector<FlattenedSpelling> Spellings = GetFlattenedSpellings(*R);
2948 for (const auto &SI : Spellings) {
2949 const std::string &Variety = SI.variety();
2950 if (Variety == "GNU")
2951 GNU.push_back(R);
2952 else if (Variety == "Declspec")
2953 Declspec.push_back(R);
2954 else if (Variety == "Microsoft")
2955 Microsoft.push_back(R);
2956 else if (Variety == "CXX11")
2957 CXX[SI.nameSpace()].push_back(R);
2958 else if (Variety == "C2x")
2959 C2x[SI.nameSpace()].push_back(R);
2960 else if (Variety == "Pragma")
2961 Pragma.push_back(R);
2962 }
2963 }
2964
2965 OS << "const llvm::Triple &T = Target.getTriple();\n";
2966 OS << "switch (Syntax) {\n";
2967 OS << "case AttrSyntax::GNU:\n";
2968 OS << " return llvm::StringSwitch<int>(Name)\n";
2969 GenerateHasAttrSpellingStringSwitch(GNU, OS, "GNU");
2970 OS << "case AttrSyntax::Declspec:\n";
2971 OS << " return llvm::StringSwitch<int>(Name)\n";
2972 GenerateHasAttrSpellingStringSwitch(Declspec, OS, "Declspec");
2973 OS << "case AttrSyntax::Microsoft:\n";
2974 OS << " return llvm::StringSwitch<int>(Name)\n";
2975 GenerateHasAttrSpellingStringSwitch(Microsoft, OS, "Microsoft");
2976 OS << "case AttrSyntax::Pragma:\n";
2977 OS << " return llvm::StringSwitch<int>(Name)\n";
2978 GenerateHasAttrSpellingStringSwitch(Pragma, OS, "Pragma");
2979 auto fn = [&OS](const char *Spelling, const char *Variety,
2980 const std::map<std::string, std::vector<Record *>> &List) {
2981 OS << "case AttrSyntax::" << Variety << ": {\n";
2982 // C++11-style attributes are further split out based on the Scope.
2983 for (auto I = List.cbegin(), E = List.cend(); I != E; ++I) {
2984 if (I != List.cbegin())
2985 OS << " else ";
2986 if (I->first.empty())
2987 OS << "if (ScopeName == \"\") {\n";
2988 else
2989 OS << "if (ScopeName == \"" << I->first << "\") {\n";
2990 OS << " return llvm::StringSwitch<int>(Name)\n";
2991 GenerateHasAttrSpellingStringSwitch(I->second, OS, Spelling, I->first);
2992 OS << "}";
2993 }
2994 OS << "\n} break;\n";
2995 };
2996 fn("CXX11", "CXX", CXX);
2997 fn("C2x", "C", C2x);
2998 OS << "}\n";
2999}

3001void EmitClangAttrSpellingListIndex(RecordKeeper &Records, raw_ostream &OS) {
3002 emitSourceFileHeader("Code to translate different attribute spellings "
3003 "into internal identifiers", OS);
3004
3005 OS << " switch (AttrKind) {\n";
3006
3007 ParsedAttrMap Attrs = getParsedAttrList(Records);
3008 for (const auto &I : Attrs) {
3009 const Record &R = *I.second;
3010 std::vector<FlattenedSpelling> Spellings = GetFlattenedSpellings(R);
3011 OS << " case AT_" << I.first << ": {\n";
3012 for (unsigned I = 0; I < Spellings.size(); ++ I) {
3013 OS << " if (Name == \"" << Spellings[I].name() << "\" && "
3014 << "SyntaxUsed == "
3015 << StringSwitch<unsigned>(Spellings[I].variety())
3016 .Case("GNU", 0)
3017 .Case("CXX11", 1)
3018 .Case("C2x", 2)
3019 .Case("Declspec", 3)
3020 .Case("Microsoft", 4)
3021 .Case("Keyword", 5)
3022 .Case("Pragma", 6)
3023 .Default(0)
3024 << " && Scope == \"" << Spellings[I].nameSpace() << "\")\n"
3025 << " return " << I << ";\n";
3026 }
3027
3028 OS << " break;\n";
3029 OS << " }\n";
3030 }
3031
3032 OS << " }\n";
3033 OS << " return 0;\n";
3034}

3036// Emits code used by RecursiveASTVisitor to visit attributes
3037void EmitClangAttrASTVisitor(RecordKeeper &Records, raw_ostream &OS) {
3038 emitSourceFileHeader("Used by RecursiveASTVisitor to visit attributes.", OS);
3039
3040 std::vector<Record*> Attrs = Records.getAllDerivedDefinitions("Attr");
3041
3042 // Write method declarations for Traverse* methods.
3043 // We emit this here because we only generate methods for attributes that
3044 // are declared as ASTNodes.
3045 OS << "#ifdef ATTR_VISITOR_DECLS_ONLY\n\n";
3046 for (const auto *Attr : Attrs) {
3047 const Record &R = *Attr;
3048 if (!R.getValueAsBit("ASTNode"))
3049 continue;
3050 OS << " bool Traverse"
3051 << R.getName() << "Attr(" << R.getName() << "Attr *A);\n";
3052 OS << " bool Visit"
3053 << R.getName() << "Attr(" << R.getName() << "Attr *A) {\n"
3054 << " return true; \n"
3055 << " }\n";
3056 }
3057 OS << "\n#else // ATTR_VISITOR_DECLS_ONLY\n\n";
3058
3059 // Write individual Traverse* methods for each attribute class.
3060 for (const auto *Attr : Attrs) {
3061 const Record &R = *Attr;
3062 if (!R.getValueAsBit("ASTNode"))
3063 continue;
3064
3065 OS << "template <typename Derived>\n"
3066 << "bool VISITORCLASS<Derived>::Traverse"
3067 << R.getName() << "Attr(" << R.getName() << "Attr *A) {\n"
3068 << " if (!getDerived().VisitAttr(A))\n"
3069 << " return false;\n"
3070 << " if (!getDerived().Visit" << R.getName() << "Attr(A))\n"
3071 << " return false;\n";
3072
3073 std::vector<Record*> ArgRecords = R.getValueAsListOfDefs("Args");
3074 for (const auto *Arg : ArgRecords)
3075 createArgument(*Arg, R.getName())->writeASTVisitorTraversal(OS);
3076
3077 OS << " return true;\n";
3078 OS << "}\n\n";
3079 }
3080
3081 // Write generic Traverse routine
3082 OS << "template <typename Derived>\n"
3083 << "bool VISITORCLASS<Derived>::TraverseAttr(Attr *A) {\n"
3084 << " if (!A)\n"
3085 << " return true;\n"
3086 << "\n"
3087 << " switch (A->getKind()) {\n";
3088
3089 for (const auto *Attr : Attrs) {
3090 const Record &R = *Attr;
3091 if (!R.getValueAsBit("ASTNode"))
3092 continue;
3093
3094 OS << " case attr::" << R.getName() << ":\n"
3095 << " return getDerived().Traverse" << R.getName() << "Attr("
3096 << "cast<" << R.getName() << "Attr>(A));\n";
3097 }
3098 OS << " }\n"; // end switch
3099 OS << " llvm_unreachable(\"bad attribute kind\");\n";
3100 OS << "}\n"; // end function
3101 OS << "#endif // ATTR_VISITOR_DECLS_ONLY\n";
3102}

3104void EmitClangAttrTemplateInstantiateHelper(const std::vector<Record *> &Attrs,
3105 raw_ostream &OS,
3106 bool AppliesToDecl) {
3107
3108 OS << " switch (At->getKind()) {\n";
3109 for (const auto *Attr : Attrs) {
3110 const Record &R = *Attr;
3111 if (!R.getValueAsBit("ASTNode"))
3112 continue;
3113 OS << " case attr::" << R.getName() << ": {\n";
3114 bool ShouldClone = R.getValueAsBit("Clone") &&
3115 (!AppliesToDecl ||
3116 R.getValueAsBit("MeaningfulToClassTemplateDefinition"));
3117
3118 if (!ShouldClone) {
3119 OS << " return nullptr;\n";
3120 OS << " }\n";
3121 continue;
3122 }
3123
3124 OS << " const auto *A = cast<"
3125 << R.getName() << "Attr>(At);\n";
3126 bool TDependent = R.getValueAsBit("TemplateDependent");
3127
3128 if (!TDependent) {
3129 OS << " return A->clone(C);\n";
3130 OS << " }\n";
3131 continue;
3132 }
3133
3134 std::vector<Record*> ArgRecords = R.getValueAsListOfDefs("Args");
3135 std::vector<std::unique_ptr<Argument>> Args;
3136 Args.reserve(ArgRecords.size());
3137
3138 for (const auto *ArgRecord : ArgRecords)
3139 Args.emplace_back(createArgument(*ArgRecord, R.getName()));
3140
3141 for (auto const &ai : Args)
3142 ai->writeTemplateInstantiation(OS);
3143
3144 OS << " return new (C) " << R.getName() << "Attr(A->getLocation(), C";
3145 for (auto const &ai : Args) {
3146 OS << ", ";
3147 ai->writeTemplateInstantiationArgs(OS);
3148 }
3149 OS << ", A->getSpellingListIndex());\n }\n";
3150 }
3151 OS << " } // end switch\n"
3152 << " llvm_unreachable(\"Unknown attribute!\");\n"
3153 << " return nullptr;\n";
3154}

3195
3196static void emitArgInfo(const Record &R, raw_ostream &OS) {
3197 // This function will count the number of arguments specified for the
3198 // attribute and emit the number of required arguments followed by the
3199 // number of optional arguments.
3200 std::vector<Record *> Args = R.getValueAsListOfDefs("Args");
3201 unsigned ArgCount = 0, OptCount = 0;
3202 bool HasVariadic = false;
3203 for (const auto *Arg : Args) {
3204 // If the arg is fake, it's the user's job to supply it: general parsing
3205 // logic shouldn't need to know anything about it.
3206 if (Arg->getValueAsBit("Fake"))
3207 continue;
3208 Arg->getValueAsBit("Optional") ? ++OptCount : ++ArgCount;
3209 if (!HasVariadic && isArgVariadic(*Arg, R.getName()))
3210 HasVariadic = true;
3211 }
3212
3213 // If there is a variadic argument, we will set the optional argument count
3214 // to its largest value. Since it's currently a 4-bit number, we set it to 15.
3215 OS << ArgCount << ", " << (HasVariadic ? 15 : OptCount);
3216}

3225static std::string GetDiagnosticSpelling(const Record &R) {
3226 std::string Ret = R.getValueAsString("DiagSpelling");
3227 if (!Ret.empty())
3228 return Ret;
3229
3230 // If we couldn't find the DiagSpelling in this object, we can check to see
3231 // if the object is one that has a base, and if it is, loop up to the Base
3232 // member recursively.
3233 std::string Super = R.getSuperClasses().back().first->getName();
3234 if (Super == "DDecl" || Super == "DStmt")
3235 return GetDiagnosticSpelling(*R.getValueAsDef("Base"));
3236
3237 return "";
3238}
3239
3240static std::string CalculateDiagnostic(const Record &S) {
3241 // If the SubjectList object has a custom diagnostic associated with it,
3242 // return that directly.
3243 const StringRef CustomDiag = S.getValueAsString("CustomDiag");
3244 if (!CustomDiag.empty())
3245 return ("\"" + Twine(CustomDiag) + "\"").str();
3246
3247 std::vector<std::string> DiagList;
3248 std::vector<Record *> Subjects = S.getValueAsListOfDefs("Subjects");
3249 for (const auto *Subject : Subjects) {
3250 const Record &R = *Subject;
3251 // Get the diagnostic text from the Decl or Stmt node given.
3252 std::string V = GetDiagnosticSpelling(R);
3253 if (V.empty()) {
3254 PrintError(R.getLoc(),
3255 "Could not determine diagnostic spelling for the node: " +
3256 R.getName() + "; please add one to DeclNodes.td");
3257 } else {
3258 // The node may contain a list of elements itself, so split the elements
3259 // by a comma, and trim any whitespace.
3260 SmallVector<StringRef, 2> Frags;
3261 llvm::SplitString(V, Frags, ",");
3262 for (auto Str : Frags) {
3263 DiagList.push_back(Str.trim());
3264 }
3265 }
3266 }
3267
3268 if (DiagList.empty()) {
3269 PrintFatalError(S.getLoc(),
3270 "Could not deduce diagnostic argument for Attr subjects");
3271 return "";
3272 }
3273
3274 // FIXME: this is not particularly good for localization purposes and ideally
3275 // should be part of the diagnostics engine itself with some sort of list
3276 // specifier.
3277
3278 // A single member of the list can be returned directly.
3279 if (DiagList.size() == 1)
3280 return '"' + DiagList.front() + '"';
3281
3282 if (DiagList.size() == 2)
3283 return '"' + DiagList[0] + " and " + DiagList[1] + '"';
3284
3285 // If there are more than two in the list, we serialize the first N - 1
3286 // elements with a comma. This leaves the string in the state: foo, bar,
3287 // baz (but misses quux). We can then add ", and " for the last element
3288 // manually.
3289 std::string Diag = llvm::join(DiagList.begin(), DiagList.end() - 1, ", ");
3290 return '"' + Diag + ", and " + *(DiagList.end() - 1) + '"';
3291}

3300static std::string functionNameForCustomAppertainsTo(const Record &Subject) {
3301 return "is" + Subject.getName().str();
3302}
3303
3304static std::string GenerateCustomAppertainsTo(const Record &Subject,
3305 raw_ostream &OS) {
3306 std::string FnName = functionNameForCustomAppertainsTo(Subject);
3307
3308 // If this code has already been generated, simply return the previous
3309 // instance of it.
3310 static std::set<std::string> CustomSubjectSet;
3311 auto I = CustomSubjectSet.find(FnName);
3312 if (I != CustomSubjectSet.end())
3313 return *I;
3314
3315 Record *Base = Subject.getValueAsDef("Base");
3316
3317 // Not currently support custom subjects within custom subjects.
3318 if (Base->isSubClassOf("SubsetSubject")) {
3319 PrintFatalError(Subject.getLoc(),
3320 "SubsetSubjects within SubsetSubjects is not supported");
3321 return "";
3322 }
3323
3324 OS << "static bool " << FnName << "(const Decl *D) {\n";
3325 OS << " if (const auto *S = dyn_cast<";
3326 OS << GetSubjectWithSuffix(Base);

3328 OS << " return " << Subject.getValueAsString("CheckCode") << ";\n";
3329 OS << " return false;\n";
3330 OS << "}\n\n";
3331
3332 CustomSubjectSet.insert(FnName);

3334}
3335
3336static std::string GenerateAppertainsTo(const Record &Attr, raw_ostream &OS) {
3337 // If the attribute does not contain a Subjects definition, then use the
3338 // default appertainsTo logic.
3339 if (Attr.isValueUnset("Subjects"))
3340 return "defaultAppertainsTo";
3341
3342 const Record *SubjectObj = Attr.getValueAsDef("Subjects");
3343 std::vector<Record*> Subjects = SubjectObj->getValueAsListOfDefs("Subjects");
3344
3345 // If the list of subjects is empty, it is assumed that the attribute
3346 // appertains to everything.
3347 if (Subjects.empty())
3348 return "defaultAppertainsTo";
3349
3350 bool Warn = SubjectObj->getValueAsDef("Diag")->getValueAsBit("Warn");
3351
3352 // Otherwise, generate an appertainsTo check specific to this attribute which
3353 // checks all of the given subjects against the Decl passed in. Return the
3354 // name of that check to the caller.
3355 //
3356 // If D is null, that means the attribute was not applied to a declaration
3357 // at all (for instance because it was applied to a type), or that the caller
3358 // has determined that the check should fail (perhaps prior to the creation
3359 // of the declaration).
3360 std::string FnName = "check" + Attr.getName().str() + "AppertainsTo";
3361 std::stringstream SS;
3362 SS << "static bool " << FnName << "(Sema &S, const ParsedAttr &Attr, ";
3363 SS << "const Decl *D) {\n";
3364 SS << " if (!D || (";
3365 for (auto I = Subjects.begin(), E = Subjects.end(); I != E; ++I) {
3366 // If the subject has custom code associated with it, generate a function
3367 // for it. The function cannot be inlined into this check (yet) because it
3368 // requires the subject to be of a specific type, and were that information
3369 // inlined here, it would not support an attribute with multiple custom
3370 // subjects.
3371 if ((*I)->isSubClassOf("SubsetSubject")) {
3372 SS << "!" << GenerateCustomAppertainsTo(**I, OS) << "(D)";
3373 } else {
3374 SS << "!isa<" << GetSubjectWithSuffix(*I) << ">(D)";
3375 }
3376
3377 if (I + 1 != E)
3378 SS << " && ";
3379 }
3380 SS << ")) {\n";
3381 SS << " S.Diag(Attr.getLoc(), diag::";
3382 SS << (Warn ? "warn_attribute_wrong_decl_type_str" :
3383 "err_attribute_wrong_decl_type_str");
3384 SS << ")\n";
3385 SS << " << Attr << ";
3386 SS << CalculateDiagnostic(*SubjectObj) << ";\n";
3387 SS << " return false;\n";
3388 SS << " }\n";
3389 SS << " return true;\n";
3390 SS << "}\n\n";
3391
3392 OS << SS.str();
3393 return FnName;
3394}

3396static void
3397emitAttributeMatchRules(PragmaClangAttributeSupport &PragmaAttributeSupport,
3398 raw_ostream &OS) {
3399 OS << "static bool checkAttributeMatchRuleAppliesTo(const Decl *D, "
3400 << AttributeSubjectMatchRule::EnumName << " rule) {\n";
3401 OS << " switch (rule) {\n";
3402 for (const auto &Rule : PragmaAttributeSupport.Rules) {
3403 if (Rule.isAbstractRule()) {
3404 OS << " case " << Rule.getEnumValue() << ":\n";
3405 OS << " assert(false && \"Abstract matcher rule isn't allowed\");\n";
3406 OS << " return false;\n";
3407 continue;
3408 }
3409 std::vector<Record *> Subjects = Rule.getSubjects();
3410 assert(!Subjects.empty() && "Missing subjects");
3411 OS << " case " << Rule.getEnumValue() << ":\n";
3412 OS << " return ";
3413 for (auto I = Subjects.begin(), E = Subjects.end(); I != E; ++I) {
3414 // If the subject has custom code associated with it, use the function
3415 // that was generated for GenerateAppertainsTo to check if the declaration
3416 // is valid.
3417 if ((*I)->isSubClassOf("SubsetSubject"))
3418 OS << functionNameForCustomAppertainsTo(**I) << "(D)";
3419 else
3420 OS << "isa<" << GetSubjectWithSuffix(*I) << ">(D)";
3421
3422 if (I + 1 != E)
3423 OS << " || ";
3424 }
3425 OS << ";\n";
3426 }
3427 OS << " }\n";
3428 OS << " llvm_unreachable(\"Invalid match rule\");\nreturn false;\n";
3429 OS << "}\n\n";
3430}

3480
3481static std::string GenerateTargetRequirements(const Record &Attr,
3482 const ParsedAttrMap &Dupes,
3483 raw_ostream &OS) {
3484 // If the attribute is not a target specific attribute, return the default
3485 // target handler.
3486 if (!Attr.isSubClassOf("TargetSpecificAttr"))
3487 return "defaultTargetRequirements";
3488
3489 // Get the list of architectures to be tested for.
3490 const Record *R = Attr.getValueAsDef("Target");
3491 std::vector<StringRef> Arches = R->getValueAsListOfStrings("Arches");
3492
3493 // If there are other attributes which share the same parsed attribute kind,
3494 // such as target-specific attributes with a shared spelling, collapse the
3495 // duplicate architectures. This is required because a shared target-specific
3496 // attribute has only one ParsedAttr::Kind enumeration value, but it
3497 // applies to multiple target architectures. In order for the attribute to be
3498 // considered valid, all of its architectures need to be included.
3499 if (!Attr.isValueUnset("ParseKind")) {
3500 const StringRef APK = Attr.getValueAsString("ParseKind");
3501 for (const auto &I : Dupes) {
3502 if (I.first == APK) {
3503 std::vector<StringRef> DA =
3504 I.second->getValueAsDef("Target")->getValueAsListOfStrings(
3505 "Arches");
3506 Arches.insert(Arches.end(), DA.begin(), DA.end());
3507 }
3508 }
3509 }
3510
3511 std::string FnName = "isTarget";
3512 std::string Test;
3513 GenerateTargetSpecificAttrChecks(R, Arches, Test, &FnName);
3514
3515 // If this code has already been generated, simply return the previous
3516 // instance of it.
3517 static std::set<std::string> CustomTargetSet;
3518 auto I = CustomTargetSet.find(FnName);
3519 if (I != CustomTargetSet.end())
3520 return *I;
3521
3522 OS << "static bool " << FnName << "(const TargetInfo &Target) {\n";
3523 OS << " const llvm::Triple &T = Target.getTriple();\n";
3524 OS << " return " << Test << ";\n";
3525 OS << "}\n\n";
3526
3527 CustomTargetSet.insert(FnName);
3528 return FnName;
3529}

3538static std::string GenerateSpellingIndexToSemanticSpelling(const Record &Attr,
3539 raw_ostream &OS) {
3540 // If the attribute does not have a semantic form, we can bail out early.
3541 if (!Attr.getValueAsBit("ASTNode"))
3542 return "defaultSpellingIndexToSemanticSpelling";
3543
3544 std::vector<FlattenedSpelling> Spellings = GetFlattenedSpellings(Attr);
3545
3546 // If there are zero or one spellings, or all of the spellings share the same
3547 // name, we can also bail out early.

3549 return "defaultSpellingIndexToSemanticSpelling";

3554 std::string Name = Attr.getName().str() + "AttrSpellingMap";

3557 OS << Enum;
3558 OS << " unsigned Idx = Attr.getAttributeSpellingListIndex();\n";
3559 WriteSemanticSpellingSwitch("Idx", SemanticToSyntacticMap, OS);
3560 OS << "}\n\n";
3561
3562 return Name;

3573/// Emits the parsed attribute helpers
3574void EmitClangAttrParsedAttrImpl(RecordKeeper &Records, raw_ostream &OS) {
3575 emitSourceFileHeader("Parsed attribute helpers", OS);
3576
3577 PragmaClangAttributeSupport &PragmaAttributeSupport =
3578 getPragmaAttributeSupport(Records);
3579
3580 // Get the list of parsed attributes, and accept the optional list of
3581 // duplicates due to the ParseKind.
3582 ParsedAttrMap Dupes;
3583 ParsedAttrMap Attrs = getParsedAttrList(Records, &Dupes);
3584
3585 // Generate the default appertainsTo, target and language option diagnostic,
3586 // and spelling list index mapping methods.
3587 GenerateDefaultAppertainsTo(OS);
3588 GenerateDefaultLangOptRequirements(OS);
3589 GenerateDefaultTargetRequirements(OS);
3590 GenerateDefaultSpellingIndexToSemanticSpelling(OS);
3591
3592 // Generate the appertainsTo diagnostic methods and write their names into
3593 // another mapping. At the same time, generate the AttrInfoMap object
3594 // contents. Due to the reliance on generated code, use separate streams so
3595 // that code will not be interleaved.
3596 std::string Buffer;
3597 raw_string_ostream SS {Buffer};
3598 for (auto I = Attrs.begin(), E = Attrs.end(); I != E; ++I) {
3599 // TODO: If the attribute's kind appears in the list of duplicates, that is
3600 // because it is a target-specific attribute that appears multiple times.
3601 // It would be beneficial to test whether the duplicates are "similar
3602 // enough" to each other to not cause problems. For instance, check that
3603 // the spellings are identical, and custom parsing rules match, etc.
3604
3605 // We need to generate struct instances based off ParsedAttrInfo from
3606 // ParsedAttr.cpp.
3607 SS << " { ";
3608 emitArgInfo(*I->second, SS);
3609 SS << ", " << I->second->getValueAsBit("HasCustomParsing");
3610 SS << ", " << I->second->isSubClassOf("TargetSpecificAttr");
3611 SS << ", "
3612 << (I->second->isSubClassOf("TypeAttr") ||
3613 I->second->isSubClassOf("DeclOrTypeAttr"));
3614 SS << ", " << I->second->isSubClassOf("StmtAttr");
3615 SS << ", " << IsKnownToGCC(*I->second);
3616 SS << ", " << PragmaAttributeSupport.isAttributedSupported(*I->second);
3617 SS << ", " << GenerateAppertainsTo(*I->second, OS);
3618 SS << ", " << GenerateLangOptRequirements(*I->second, OS);
3619 SS << ", " << GenerateTargetRequirements(*I->second, Dupes, OS);
3620 SS << ", " << GenerateSpellingIndexToSemanticSpelling(*I->second, OS);
3621 SS << ", "
3622 << PragmaAttributeSupport.generateStrictConformsTo(*I->second, OS);
3623 SS << " }";
3624
3625 if (I + 1 != E)
3626 SS << ",";
3627
3628 SS << " // AT_" << I->first << "\n";
3629 }
3630
3631 OS << "static const ParsedAttrInfo AttrInfoMap[ParsedAttr::UnknownAttribute "
3632 "+ 1] = {\n";
3633 OS << SS.str();
3634 OS << "};\n\n";
3635
3636 // Generate the attribute match rules.
3637 emitAttributeMatchRules(PragmaAttributeSupport, OS);
3638}
3639
3640// Emits the kind list of parsed attributes
3641void EmitClangAttrParsedAttrKinds(RecordKeeper &Records, raw_ostream &OS) {
3642 emitSourceFileHeader("Attribute name matcher", OS);
3643
3644 std::vector<Record *> Attrs = Records.getAllDerivedDefinitions("Attr");
3645 std::vector<StringMatcher::StringPair> GNU, Declspec, Microsoft, CXX11,
3646 Keywords, Pragma, C2x;
3647 std::set<std::string> Seen;
3648 for (const auto *A : Attrs) {
3649 const Record &Attr = *A;
3650
3651 bool SemaHandler = Attr.getValueAsBit("SemaHandler");
3652 bool Ignored = Attr.getValueAsBit("Ignored");
3653 if (SemaHandler || Ignored) {
3654 // Attribute spellings can be shared between target-specific attributes,
3655 // and can be shared between syntaxes for the same attribute. For
3656 // instance, an attribute can be spelled GNU<"interrupt"> for an ARM-
3657 // specific attribute, or MSP430-specific attribute. Additionally, an
3658 // attribute can be spelled GNU<"dllexport"> and Declspec<"dllexport">
3659 // for the same semantic attribute. Ultimately, we need to map each of
3660 // these to a single ParsedAttr::Kind value, but the StringMatcher
3661 // class cannot handle duplicate match strings. So we generate a list of
3662 // string to match based on the syntax, and emit multiple string matchers
3663 // depending on the syntax used.
3664 std::string AttrName;
3665 if (Attr.isSubClassOf("TargetSpecificAttr") &&
3666 !Attr.isValueUnset("ParseKind")) {
3667 AttrName = Attr.getValueAsString("ParseKind");
3668 if (Seen.find(AttrName) != Seen.end())
3669 continue;
3670 Seen.insert(AttrName);
3671 } else
3672 AttrName = NormalizeAttrName(StringRef(Attr.getName())).str();
3673
3674 std::vector<FlattenedSpelling> Spellings = GetFlattenedSpellings(Attr);
3675 for (const auto &S : Spellings) {
3676 const std::string &RawSpelling = S.name();
3677 std::vector<StringMatcher::StringPair> *Matches = nullptr;
3678 std::string Spelling;
3679 const std::string &Variety = S.variety();
3680 if (Variety == "CXX11") {
3681 Matches = &CXX11;
3682 Spelling += S.nameSpace();
3683 Spelling += "::";
3684 } else if (Variety == "C2x") {
3685 Matches = &C2x;
3686 Spelling += S.nameSpace();
3687 Spelling += "::";
3688 } else if (Variety == "GNU")
3689 Matches = &GNU;
3690 else if (Variety == "Declspec")
3691 Matches = &Declspec;
3692 else if (Variety == "Microsoft")
3693 Matches = &Microsoft;
3694 else if (Variety == "Keyword")
3695 Matches = &Keywords;
3696 else if (Variety == "Pragma")
3697 Matches = &Pragma;
3698
3699 assert(Matches && "Unsupported spelling variety found");
3700
3701 if (Variety == "GNU")
3702 Spelling += NormalizeGNUAttrSpelling(RawSpelling);
3703 else
3704 Spelling += RawSpelling;
3705
3706 if (SemaHandler)
3707 Matches->push_back(StringMatcher::StringPair(
3708 Spelling, "return ParsedAttr::AT_" + AttrName + ";"));
3709 else
3710 Matches->push_back(StringMatcher::StringPair(
3711 Spelling, "return ParsedAttr::IgnoredAttribute;"));
3712 }
3713 }
3714 }
3715
3716 OS << "static ParsedAttr::Kind getAttrKind(StringRef Name, ";
3717 OS << "ParsedAttr::Syntax Syntax) {\n";
3718 OS << " if (ParsedAttr::AS_GNU == Syntax) {\n";
3719 StringMatcher("Name", GNU, OS).Emit();
3720 OS << " } else if (ParsedAttr::AS_Declspec == Syntax) {\n";
3721 StringMatcher("Name", Declspec, OS).Emit();
3722 OS << " } else if (ParsedAttr::AS_Microsoft == Syntax) {\n";
3723 StringMatcher("Name", Microsoft, OS).Emit();
3724 OS << " } else if (ParsedAttr::AS_CXX11 == Syntax) {\n";
3725 StringMatcher("Name", CXX11, OS).Emit();
3726 OS << " } else if (ParsedAttr::AS_C2x == Syntax) {\n";
3727 StringMatcher("Name", C2x, OS).Emit();
3728 OS << " } else if (ParsedAttr::AS_Keyword == Syntax || ";
3729 OS << "ParsedAttr::AS_ContextSensitiveKeyword == Syntax) {\n";
3730 StringMatcher("Name", Keywords, OS).Emit();
3731 OS << " } else if (ParsedAttr::AS_Pragma == Syntax) {\n";
3732 StringMatcher("Name", Pragma, OS).Emit();
3733 OS << " }\n";
3734 OS << " return ParsedAttr::UnknownAttribute;\n"
3735 << "}\n";
3736}

3738// Emits the code to dump an attribute.
3739void EmitClangAttrTextNodeDump(RecordKeeper &Records, raw_ostream &OS) {
3740 emitSourceFileHeader("Attribute text node dumper", OS);
3741
3742 std::vector<Record*> Attrs = Records.getAllDerivedDefinitions("Attr"), Args;
3743 for (const auto *Attr : Attrs) {
3744 const Record &R = *Attr;
3745 if (!R.getValueAsBit("ASTNode"))
3746 continue;
3747
3748 // If the attribute has a semantically-meaningful name (which is determined
3749 // by whether there is a Spelling enumeration for it), then write out the
3750 // spelling used for the attribute.
3751
3752 std::string FunctionContent;
3753 llvm::raw_string_ostream SS(FunctionContent);
3754
3755 std::vector<FlattenedSpelling> Spellings = GetFlattenedSpellings(R);
3756 if (Spellings.size() > 1 && !SpellingNamesAreCommon(Spellings))
3757 SS << " OS << \" \" << A->getSpelling();\n";
3758
3759 Args = R.getValueAsListOfDefs("Args");
3760 for (const auto *Arg : Args)
3761 createArgument(*Arg, R.getName())->writeDump(SS);
3762
3763 if (SS.tell()) {
3764 OS << " void Visit" << R.getName() << "Attr(const " << R.getName()
3765 << "Attr *A) {\n";
3766 if (!Args.empty())
3767 OS << " const auto *SA = cast<" << R.getName()
3768 << "Attr>(A); (void)SA;\n";
3769 OS << SS.str();
3770 OS << " }\n";
3771 }
3772 }
3773}

3818enum class SpellingKind {
3819 GNU,
3820 CXX11,
3821 C2x,
3822 Declspec,
3823 Microsoft,
3824 Keyword,
3825 Pragma,
3826};
3827static const size_t NumSpellingKinds = (size_t)SpellingKind::Pragma + 1;
3828
3829class SpellingList {
3830 std::vector<std::string> Spellings[NumSpellingKinds];
3831
3832public:
3833 ArrayRef<std::string> operator[](SpellingKind K) const {
3834 return Spellings[(size_t)K];
3835 }
3836
3837 void add(const Record &Attr, FlattenedSpelling Spelling) {
3838 SpellingKind Kind = StringSwitch<SpellingKind>(Spelling.variety())
3839 .Case("GNU", SpellingKind::GNU)
3840 .Case("CXX11", SpellingKind::CXX11)
3841 .Case("C2x", SpellingKind::C2x)
3842 .Case("Declspec", SpellingKind::Declspec)
3843 .Case("Microsoft", SpellingKind::Microsoft)
3844 .Case("Keyword", SpellingKind::Keyword)
3845 .Case("Pragma", SpellingKind::Pragma);
3846 std::string Name;
3847 if (!Spelling.nameSpace().empty()) {
3848 switch (Kind) {
3849 case SpellingKind::CXX11:
3850 case SpellingKind::C2x:
3851 Name = Spelling.nameSpace() + "::";
3852 break;
3853 case SpellingKind::Pragma:
3854 Name = Spelling.nameSpace() + " ";
3855 break;
3856 default:
3857 PrintFatalError(Attr.getLoc(), "Unexpected namespace in spelling");
3858 }
3859 }
3860 Name += Spelling.name();
3861
3862 Spellings[(size_t)Kind].push_back(Name);
3863 }
3864};
3865
3866class DocumentationData {
3867public:
3868 const Record *Documentation;
3869 const Record *Attribute;
3870 std::string Heading;
3871 SpellingList SupportedSpellings;
3872
3873 DocumentationData(const Record &Documentation, const Record &Attribute,
3874 std::pair<std::string, SpellingList> HeadingAndSpellings)
3875 : Documentation(&Documentation), Attribute(&Attribute),
3876 Heading(std::move(HeadingAndSpellings.first)),
3877 SupportedSpellings(std::move(HeadingAndSpellings.second)) {}
3878};
3879
3880static void WriteCategoryHeader(const Record *DocCategory,
3881 raw_ostream &OS) {
3882 const StringRef Name = DocCategory->getValueAsString("Name");
3883 OS << Name << "\n" << std::string(Name.size(), '=') << "\n";
3884
3885 // If there is content, print that as well.
3886 const StringRef ContentStr = DocCategory->getValueAsString("Content");
3887 // Trim leading and trailing newlines and spaces.
3888 OS << ContentStr.trim();
3889
3890 OS << "\n\n";
3891}
3892
3893static std::pair<std::string, SpellingList>
3894GetAttributeHeadingAndSpellings(const Record &Documentation,
3895 const Record &Attribute) {
3896 // FIXME: there is no way to have a per-spelling category for the attribute
3897 // documentation. This may not be a limiting factor since the spellings
3898 // should generally be consistently applied across the category.
3899
3900 std::vector<FlattenedSpelling> Spellings = GetFlattenedSpellings(Attribute);
3901 if (Spellings.empty())
3902 PrintFatalError(Attribute.getLoc(),
3903 "Attribute has no supported spellings; cannot be "
3904 "documented");
3905
3906 // Determine the heading to be used for this attribute.
3907 std::string Heading = Documentation.getValueAsString("Heading");
3908 if (Heading.empty()) {
3909 // If there's only one spelling, we can simply use that.
3910 if (Spellings.size() == 1)
3911 Heading = Spellings.begin()->name();
3912 else {
3913 std::set<std::string> Uniques;
3914 for (auto I = Spellings.begin(), E = Spellings.end();
3915 I != E && Uniques.size() <= 1; ++I) {
3916 std::string Spelling = NormalizeNameForSpellingComparison(I->name());
3917 Uniques.insert(Spelling);
3918 }
3919 // If the semantic map has only one spelling, that is sufficient for our
3920 // needs.
3921 if (Uniques.size() == 1)
3922 Heading = *Uniques.begin();
3923 }
3924 }
3925
3926 // If the heading is still empty, it is an error.
3927 if (Heading.empty())
3928 PrintFatalError(Attribute.getLoc(),
3929 "This attribute requires a heading to be specified");
3930
3931 SpellingList SupportedSpellings;
3932 for (const auto &I : Spellings)
3933 SupportedSpellings.add(Attribute, I);
3934
3935 return std::make_pair(std::move(Heading), std::move(SupportedSpellings));
3936}
3937
3938static void WriteDocumentation(RecordKeeper &Records,
3939 const DocumentationData &Doc, raw_ostream &OS) {
3940 OS << Doc.Heading << "\n" << std::string(Doc.Heading.length(), '-') << "\n";
3941
3942 // List what spelling syntaxes the attribute supports.
3943 OS << ".. csv-table:: Supported Syntaxes\n";
3944 OS << " :header: \"GNU\", \"C++11\", \"C2x\", \"``__declspec``\",";
3945 OS << " \"Keyword\", \"``#pragma``\", \"``#pragma clang attribute``\"\n\n";
3946 OS << " \"";
3947 for (size_t Kind = 0; Kind != NumSpellingKinds; ++Kind) {
3948 SpellingKind K = (SpellingKind)Kind;
3949 // TODO: List Microsoft (IDL-style attribute) spellings once we fully
3950 // support them.
3951 if (K == SpellingKind::Microsoft)
3952 continue;
3953
3954 bool PrintedAny = false;
3955 for (StringRef Spelling : Doc.SupportedSpellings[K]) {
3956 if (PrintedAny)
3957 OS << " |br| ";
3958 OS << "``" << Spelling << "``";
3959 PrintedAny = true;
3960 }
3961
3962 OS << "\",\"";
3963 }
3964
3965 if (getPragmaAttributeSupport(Records).isAttributedSupported(
3966 *Doc.Attribute))
3967 OS << "Yes";
3968 OS << "\"\n\n";
3969
3970 // If the attribute is deprecated, print a message about it, and possibly
3971 // provide a replacement attribute.
3972 if (!Doc.Documentation->isValueUnset("Deprecated")) {
3973 OS << "This attribute has been deprecated, and may be removed in a future "
3974 << "version of Clang.";
3975 const Record &Deprecated = *Doc.Documentation->getValueAsDef("Deprecated");
3976 const StringRef Replacement = Deprecated.getValueAsString("Replacement");
3977 if (!Replacement.empty())
3978 OS << " This attribute has been superseded by ``" << Replacement
3979 << "``.";
3980 OS << "\n\n";
3981 }
3982
3983 const StringRef ContentStr = Doc.Documentation->getValueAsString("Content");
3984 // Trim leading and trailing newlines and spaces.
3985 OS << ContentStr.trim();
3986
3987 OS << "\n\n\n";
3988}

3990void EmitClangAttrDocs(RecordKeeper &Records, raw_ostream &OS) {
3991 // Get the documentation introduction paragraph.
3992 const Record *Documentation = Records.getDef("GlobalDocumentation");
3993 if (!Documentation) {
3994 PrintFatalError("The Documentation top-level definition is missing, "
3995 "no documentation will be generated.");
3996 return;
3997 }
3998
3999 OS << Documentation->getValueAsString("Intro") << "\n";
4000
4001 // Gather the Documentation lists from each of the attributes, based on the
4002 // category provided.
4003 std::vector<Record *> Attrs = Records.getAllDerivedDefinitions("Attr");
4004 std::map<const Record *, std::vector<DocumentationData>> SplitDocs;
4005 for (const auto *A : Attrs) {
4006 const Record &Attr = *A;
4007 std::vector<Record *> Docs = Attr.getValueAsListOfDefs("Documentation");
4008 for (const auto *D : Docs) {
4009 const Record &Doc = *D;
4010 const Record *Category = Doc.getValueAsDef("Category");
4011 // If the category is "undocumented", then there cannot be any other
4012 // documentation categories (otherwise, the attribute would become
4013 // documented).
4014 const StringRef Cat = Category->getValueAsString("Name");
4015 bool Undocumented = Cat == "Undocumented";
4016 if (Undocumented && Docs.size() > 1)
4017 PrintFatalError(Doc.getLoc(),
4018 "Attribute is \"Undocumented\", but has multiple "
4019 "documentation categories");
4020
4021 if (!Undocumented)
4022 SplitDocs[Category].push_back(DocumentationData(
4023 Doc, Attr, GetAttributeHeadingAndSpellings(Doc, Attr)));
4024 }
4025 }
4026
4027 // Having split the attributes out based on what documentation goes where,
4028 // we can begin to generate sections of documentation.
4029 for (auto &I : SplitDocs) {
4030 WriteCategoryHeader(I.first, OS);
4031
4032 llvm::sort(I.second,
4033 [](const DocumentationData &D1, const DocumentationData &D2) {
4034 return D1.Heading < D2.Heading;
4035 });
4036
4037 // Walk over each of the attributes in the category and write out their
4038 // documentation.
4039 for (const auto &Doc : I.second)
4040 WriteDocumentation(Records, Doc, OS);
4041 }
4042}

4044void EmitTestPragmaAttributeSupportedAttributes(RecordKeeper &Records,
4045 raw_ostream &OS) {
4046 PragmaClangAttributeSupport Support = getPragmaAttributeSupport(Records);
4047 ParsedAttrMap Attrs = getParsedAttrList(Records);
4048 OS << "#pragma clang attribute supports the following attributes:\n";
4049 for (const auto &I : Attrs) {
4050 if (!Support.isAttributedSupported(*I.second))
4051 continue;
4052 OS << I.first;
4053 if (I.second->isValueUnset("Subjects")) {
4054 OS << " ()\n";
4055 continue;
4056 }
4057 const Record *SubjectObj = I.second->getValueAsDef("Subjects");
4058 std::vector<Record *> Subjects =
4059 SubjectObj->getValueAsListOfDefs("Subjects");
4060 OS << " (";
4061 for (const auto &Subject : llvm::enumerate(Subjects)) {
4062 if (Subject.index())
4063 OS << ", ";
4064 PragmaClangAttributeSupport::RuleOrAggregateRuleSet &RuleSet =
4065 Support.SubjectsToRules.find(Subject.value())->getSecond();
4066 if (RuleSet.isRule()) {
4067 OS << RuleSet.getRule().getEnumValueName();
4068 continue;
4069 }
4070 OS << "(";
4071 for (const auto &Rule : llvm::enumerate(RuleSet.getAggregateRuleSet())) {
4072 if (Rule.index())
4073 OS << ", ";
4074 OS << Rule.value().getEnumValueName();
4075 }
4076 OS << ")";
4077 }
4078 OS << ")\n";
4079 }
4080 OS << "End of supported attributes.\n";
4081}
